Q1.2:
INTRODUCTION
You are invited to participate in a research study aimed at identifying gaps and opportunities for improving design tools, methodologies and guidelines to support sustainable cooling designs. You are being asked to complete an online survey that explores design approaches and tools used by practitioners to implement natural cooling strategies in buildings. 

 
The main objectives for the survey are to:

1. Understand which performance indicators, rules-of-thumb, and design tools practitioners are currently using to integrate natural cooling into their designs.

2. Understand the limitations of the current generation of design tools and guidelines.

3. Gauge interest in a prototype of a new modeling tool for natural cooling design.



TIME INVOLVEMENT

Your participation will take approximately 10 to 20 minutes.



RISKS AND BENEFITS

There are no risks associated with this study. There are also no direct benefits expected to result from this study. The benefits that may reasonably be expected to result from this study are greater knowledge about current design approaches, barriers and opportunities related to the use of natural cooling strategies in building design. Study data will be stored securely, in compliance with Stanford University standards, minimizing the risk of confidentiality breach. We cannot and do not guarantee or promise that you will receive any benefits from this study. 



PAYMENTS:
You will receive a USD$25 gift card sent to the email address you provide. 



PARTICIPANT‚ÄôS RIGHTS:

If you have read this form and have decided to participate in this survey, please understand your participation is voluntary and you have the right to withdraw your consent or discontinue participation at any time without penalty or loss of benefits to which you are otherwise entitled. The alternative is not to participate. You have the right to refuse to answer particular questions. The results of this research study may be presented at scientific or professional meetings or published in scientific journals. Your individual privacy will be maintained in all published and written data resulting from the study.



CONTACT INFORMATION

Questions: If you have any questions, concerns or complaints about this research, its procedures, risks and benefits, contact the Protocol Director, Catherine Gorle, at  or Investigator at .

Independent Contact: If you are not satisfied with how this study is being conducted, or if you have any concerns, complaints, or general questions about the research or your rights as a participant, please contact the Stanford Institutional Review Board (IRB) to speak to someone independent of the research team at 650-723-2480 or toll free at 1-866-680-2906, or email at IRB2-Manager@lists.stanford.edu. You can also write to the Stanford IRB, Stanford University, 3000 El Camino Real, Five Palo Alto Square, 4th Floor, Palo Alto, CA 94306.

Q7.6: I've been a natural ventilation consultant for almost 20 years and helped develop the tool I use (which is far from perfect!). Our number one rule of thumb is that natural ventilation should be designed for a zero wind condition. Once they're designed, we should make sure that any wind helps us (not hurts us). The reason why I don't see much use to this tool for my professional work is because I didn't see any buoyancy on heat gain simulations. Without that an architect may think they can make a glassy building and the natural ventilation will work wonderfully. I would strongly recommend including temperature data into your tool.

Q7.6:
We are just wrapping up a mixed mode building for Valley Health Plan (VHP) in south San Jose. It involves the extensive renovation of a market rate, cold shell, developer building built in +/-2000 but never occupied. 

It is a 98,000sf, two-story tilt up building ill-suited to natural ventilation due to its deep floor plate. VHP offices will occupy the second floor with some functions and additional meeting rooms on the ground floor. Most of the ground floor is "warm shell" for future tenants. The users wanted the project to be naturally ventilated. Due to many constraints, natural ventilation was pursued on the second floor only. 

(16) large roof monitors with operable windows were added to the roof, operable windows were installed in the upgraded windows all the way around the second floor, fans are located throughout the open office areas, and displacement ventilation strategies were utilized. Night flushing mode is controlled based on temperature, humidity, and air quality. User overrides by zone are possible during the occupied hours.
